A use case describes a complete interaction between an <strong>actor</strong> (user, system, device) and the system to achieve a <strong>goal</strong>. It's the primary tool for communicating requirements between business and tech.

<pre><code>// Use Case: Create Delivery
// Actor: Dispatcher
// Precondition: Driver is available, route is validated
// Main Flow:
//   1. Dispatcher selects driver and route
//   2. System validates capacity and time window
//   3. System assigns delivery and notifies driver
//   4. System publishes DeliveryCreated event
// Postcondition: Delivery exists in PLANNED status
// Extensions:
//   2a. Capacity exceeded → System suggests alternative driver
//   3a. Driver unavailable → System returns to step 1</code></pre>

<strong>Interview value:</strong> When asked "How do you gather requirements?" — use cases show structured thinking. When asked "Design a delivery system" — start with use cases before jumping to code.

An <strong>actor</strong> is anything external that interacts with your system:

• <strong>Primary actor:</strong> Initiates the use case (Dispatcher, Customer)
• <strong>Supporting actor:</strong> Provides a service (Payment Gateway, Notification Service)
• <strong>Offstage actor:</strong> Has interest but doesn't interact directly (Compliance Team)

<pre><code>// REWE Delivery System — Actors:
// Primary:   Dispatcher, Driver, Customer
// Supporting: Route Optimization API, Kafka, Payment Service
// Offstage:  Operations Manager (receives reports)

// System boundary defines WHAT you're building:
// Inside: delivery-service, route-service, notification-service
// Outside: driver's phone app (actor), warehouse system (actor)</code></pre>

<strong>Common mistake in interviews:</strong> Describing implementation details instead of user goals. Use case = WHAT the system does for the actor, not HOW it does it internally.

Class diagrams are NOT just for documentation — they're a <strong>thinking tool</strong> for:

• <strong>Domain modeling:</strong> Before coding, sketch entities and relationships
• <strong>API design:</strong> Define DTOs, request/response objects
• <strong>Interview whiteboard:</strong> Communicate your design visually

<pre><code>// Domain Model: Delivery System
//
// ┌─────────────┐       ┌──────────┐
// │  Delivery   │──────▶│  Driver  │
// ├─────────────┤  1..1 ├──────────┤
// │ id          │       │ id       │
// │ status      │       │ name     │
// │ scheduledAt │       │ license  │
// │ completedAt │       │ status   │
// └─────────────┘       └──────────┘
//       │ 1..*
//       ▼
// ┌──────────┐
// │   Stop   │
// ├──────────┤
// │ address  │
// │ sequence │
// │ type     │
// └──────────┘</code></pre>

<strong>In Spring Boot:</strong> Class diagram maps directly to @Entity classes + their @ManyToOne/@OneToMany relationships.

| Relationship | UML | Java/JPA | Example |
|---|---|---|---|
| Association (1:1) | ─── | @OneToOne | Delivery → Invoice |
| Association (1:N) | ──◇ | @OneToMany | Driver → List<Delivery> |
| Association (N:M) | ◇──◇ | @ManyToMany | Driver ↔ Zone |
| Composition (owns) | ──◆ | cascade=ALL, orphanRemoval | Delivery ◆── Stops |
| Aggregation (uses) | ──◇ | no cascade | Delivery ◇── Driver |
| Inheritance | ──▷ | extends | ExpressDelivery ▷ Delivery |

<pre><code>// Composition: Delivery OWNS its stops (delete delivery = delete stops)
@Entity
public class Delivery {
    @OneToMany(cascade = ALL, orphanRemoval = true)
    private List<Stop> stops; // composition

    @ManyToOne // aggregation: delivery USES driver but doesn't own it
    private Driver driver;
}</code></pre>

<strong>Interview tip:</strong> When drawing on whiteboard, always clarify: "Is this composition (lifecycle dependency) or aggregation (reference only)?" Shows you think about ownership and cascading.

Sequence diagrams show the TIME-ORDERED interaction between objects. Essential for:
• Explaining complex flows in interviews
• Documenting integration between services
• Finding design problems (too many calls, circular dependencies)

<pre><code>// Sequence: Create Delivery
//
// Dispatcher     Controller     Service      Repository     Kafka
//     │               │            │             │            │
//     │──POST /del──▶│            │             │            │
//     │               │──create()─▶│             │            │
//     │               │            │──validate()─┐            │
//     │               │            │◀────────────┘            │
//     │               │            │──save()────▶│            │
//     │               │            │◀────────────│            │
//     │               │            │──publish()──────────────▶│
//     │               │◀───dto─────│             │            │
//     │◀──201─────────│            │             │            │

// What this reveals:
// - Clear layering (controller→service→repo)
// - Kafka publish AFTER persist (not inside transaction)
// - Single responsibility per object</code></pre>

Seniors don't just MAKE decisions — they DOCUMENT and DEFEND them.

<pre><code>// ADR-014: Use Kafka for delivery events (not REST callbacks)
//
// Status: Accepted
// Context: Delivery lifecycle events need to reach 5+ consumers
//          (billing, analytics, driver-app, warehouse, customer-notify)
//
// Decision: Publish events to Kafka topic
//
// Consequences:
//   + Decoupled: new consumers without changing producer
//   + Reliable: persistent, replayable, ordered per delivery
//   + Scalable: partition by delivery-id, consumers scale independently
//   - Added infrastructure (Kafka cluster)
//   - Eventual consistency (consumers process asynchronously)
//
// Alternatives rejected:
//   REST webhooks: coupling, retry complexity, no replay
//   Database polling: latency, load on DB, no ordering guarantee
//   Shared database: tight coupling between services</code></pre>

<strong>Interview tip:</strong> When explaining a design choice, structure as: CONTEXT → DECISION → CONSEQUENCES (pros AND cons) → ALTERNATIVES REJECTED.

| Style | When | Trade-off | REWE context |
|---|---|---|---|
| Monolith | Small team, simple domain | Fast to develop, hard to scale parts independently | Legacy systems |
| Modular monolith | Medium complexity, one team | Best of both: modular but single deploy | Transition step |
| Microservices | Large team, independent scaling | Operational complexity, distributed transactions | delivery-service, route-service |
| Event-driven | Async workflows, decoupling | Eventual consistency, debugging complexity | Kafka-based architecture |
| CQRS | Read/write with different models | Complexity, eventual consistency | Driver dashboard (read) vs commands |

<pre><code>// REWE TRAB architecture (inferred):
// Microservices + Event-driven
//
// delivery-service ──Kafka──▶ billing-service
//        │                    ▲
//        │                    │
//        ▼                    │
// route-service        analytics-service
//        │
//        ▼
// driver-app (mobile)
//
// Why microservices here:
// - Teams work independently (TRAB owns delivery)
// - Different scaling needs (route = CPU, delivery = I/O)
// - Different deployment cadence</code></pre>

Data modeling BEFORE coding prevents expensive refactoring later.

<pre><code>// Step 1: Identify entities (nouns in requirements)
// "A DRIVER is assigned to a DELIVERY with multiple STOPS
//  at specific ADDRESSES in a ZONE"
//
// Entities: Driver, Delivery, Stop, Address, Zone

// Step 2: Identify relationships and cardinality
// Driver (1) ──delivers──▶ (0..*) Delivery
// Delivery (1) ──has──▶ (1..*) Stop
// Stop (1) ──at──▶ (1) Address
// Zone (1) ──contains──▶ (0..*) Address
// Driver (0..*) ──works_in──▶ (1..*) Zone  [M:N]

// Step 3: Define attributes
// Delivery: id, status, scheduledAt, completedAt, priority
// Stop: sequence, type(PICKUP|DROPOFF), estimatedArrival
// Driver: id, name, license, vehicleType, maxCapacity</code></pre>

<strong>In interview:</strong> Start with entities and relationships BEFORE discussing tables or code. Shows you think at domain level.

Full normalization theory (1NF→5NF) matters less than practical rules:

<pre><code>// ❌ Denormalized (problematic)
// delivery table:
// id | driver_name | driver_license | driver_phone | stop_1 | stop_2
// Problems: update anomaly (driver changes name → update all rows),
//           insert anomaly (can't add driver without delivery),
//           repeating groups (stop_1, stop_2... stop_N?)

// ✅ Normalized (3NF)
// driver: id, name, license, phone
// delivery: id, driver_id(FK), status, scheduled_at
// stop: id, delivery_id(FK), sequence, address, type

// When to DENORMALIZE (intentionally):
// - Read-heavy queries joining 5+ tables → materialized view
// - Audit/history table → snapshot all fields at point in time
// - Event payload → self-contained (no JOINs needed to process)
// - Reporting/analytics → star schema (fact + dimensions)</code></pre>

<strong>Senior answer:</strong> "I normalize by default (3NF), then denormalize SPECIFIC paths for performance with measured evidence, not premature optimization."

| Audience | Diagram | Level of detail |
|---|---|---|
| Business/PM | Use Case diagram | Goals, actors, no tech |
| Other developers | Class + Sequence | Interfaces, interactions |
| Ops/DevOps | Deployment diagram | Infrastructure, networking |
| New team member | Component/Package | High-level structure |
| Yourself (thinking) | Whiteboard sketch | Anything that helps |

<strong>Key principle:</strong> The diagram is a COMMUNICATION TOOL, not documentation for documentation's sake. If nobody will read it, don't draw it.

<pre><code>// Interview scenario:
// "Design a delivery assignment system"
//
// Step 1: Use case (WHAT) — 30 seconds
//   "Primary use case: Dispatcher assigns delivery to driver"
//
// Step 2: Component diagram (HIGH LEVEL) — 1 minute
//   "Three services: delivery, route-optimizer, driver-availability"
//
// Step 3: Sequence diagram (HOW) — 2 minutes
//   "Let me show how they interact for assignment..."
//
// Step 4: Class diagram (DETAIL) — if asked to go deeper
//   "The domain model has Delivery, Driver, Route, Stop..."
//
// This progression shows you can operate at multiple abstraction levels.</code></pre>

The C4 model (Context, Container, Component, Code) provides consistent zoom levels:

<pre><code>// Level 1: System Context
// Who uses the system? What external systems does it talk to?
// → Dispatcher uses Delivery System, which talks to Maps API

// Level 2: Container
// What deployable units exist?
// → delivery-service (Spring Boot), PostgreSQL, Kafka, Redis

// Level 3: Component
// What are the major parts inside a container?
// → DeliveryController, RouteOptimizer, EventPublisher, DriverCache

// Level 4: Code (rarely drawn)
// Class-level detail → use IDE or auto-generated diagrams

// Interview approach:
// Start at Level 1 (context), zoom in when asked
// "Let me start with who uses this system..."
// "Zooming into the delivery-service..."
// "The assignment flow between these components..."</code></pre>

<strong>Why C4 matters for REWE:</strong> Their architecture docs likely use C4 or similar. Showing you know this vocabulary demonstrates enterprise readiness.
